The conservation properties of the full non-relativistic collision operator (Eqs.~\ref{eq:C} and \ref{eq:fp}), as well as the relativistic test-particle operator in {Eq.~(\ref{{eq:C}})}, are shown in {Fig.~\ref{{fig:conservation}}}. As an electric field is applied to supply some momentum and energy to the distribution, the parallel momentum ({Fig.~\ref{{fig:conservation}}}a) quickly reaches a steady-state value corresponding to the plasma conductivity, which differs by about a factor of two for the two operators (see below). The electric field is turned off at $t\!=\!t_0\!=\!100$ collision times (and ${Z_{\mbox{\scriptsize eff}}}\!=\!0$ is imposed to isolate the behavior of the electron-electron collision operator), at which point the parallel momentum for the operator in {Eq.~(\ref{{eq:C}})} (blue, dashed) is lost on a short time scale as the distribution relaxes back towards a Maxwellian. In contrast, the full linearized operator (black, solid) conserves parallel momentum in a pure electron plasma, as expected. 

